## 2 Device Fabrication and Measurement

The energy band diagram of the dielectric heterojunction diode can be divided into two types according to the conduction band offset between insulator and semiconductor by the definition of \(\Delta E_{C}=(E_{C-{\rm insulator}}-E_{C-{\rm Ga}_{2}{\rm O}_{3}})\). As shown in Fig. 1(a), with the positive value of \(\Delta E_{C}\), the electrons tunneling through the metal-semiconductor (MS) interface are blocked by the high barrier of insulator under reverse bias, which can effectively reduce the reverse leakage current. However, the forward current will also decrease in the presence of \(\Delta E_{C}\) under forward bias [19]. While with the negative value of \(\Delta E_{C}\), the electrons can pass through the insulator without obstruction under forward bias. On the other hand, under reverse bias, the carriers can move from anode to cathode only by tunneling through the triangular barrier at the dielectric/\(\beta\)-Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) heterojunction without the influence of the dielectric, resulting in a larger reverse leakage current. In summary, if the absolute value of \(\Delta E_{C}\) is kept small enough, the high-performance MDS diode can be demonstrated with a large breakdown voltage while maintaining good forward conduction characteristics with low on-resistance.

In the following, the band alignments between the available dielectrics and \(\beta\)-Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) are presented [20, 21] and the values of conduction band offset are also marked in Fig. 2. It is found that the material with a large value of \(\Delta E_{C}\) can only be used as an insulating gate dielectric layer in gallium oxide MOSFET such as SiO\({}_{2}\), Al\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\), HfO\({}_{2}\), and ZrO\({}_{2}\). However, with a small value of \(\Delta E_{C}\), the material can be used as an insulating layer in the dielectric heterojunction diodes, such as BaTiO\({}_{3}\)[19].

In order to study the band alignment of Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) and TiO\({}_{2}\), three samples of A (Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) bulk), B (20-nm TiO\({}_{2}\)), and C (3-nm TiO\({}_{2}\)/Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\)) were performed X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) measurement with Thermo Scientific K-Alpha XPS system using the monochromatic soft Al K\(\alpha\) (1486.6 eV) X-ray source. The TiO\({}_{2}\) layers with a thickness of 3 and 20 nm were grown directly on the \(\beta\)-Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) substrates by a Modern Chemistry Research Institute (MCRI) FH-2 atomic layer deposition (ALD) system (Xi'an MCRI, Xi'an, China). The Ti(DiPt)\({}_{4}\) precursor container was kept at 40 \({}^{\circ}\)C and a stream of N\({}_{2}\) was pushed through the container at a rate of 50 sccm to carry the Ti(DiPt)\({}_{4}\) vapor to the ALD reactor. The partial pressure of H\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{2}\) injected to the ALD reactor was controlled at about 0.1 Torr by adjusting the regulating valve upstream to the ALD reactor.

The equation of conduction band offset \(\Delta E_{C}\) is expressed as follows:

\[\Delta E_{C}=E_{G}^{\rm TiO_{2}}-E_{G}^{\rm Ga_{2}O_{3}}-\Delta E_{V}\]

where \(E_{G}^{\rm TiO_{2}},E_{G}^{\rm Ga_{2}O_{3}}\), and \(\Delta E_{V}\) are the bandgaps for TiO\({}_{2}\), Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\), and the valence band offset for TiO\({}_{2}\)/Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) interface, respectively. The photograph excitation and photoemission of electrons with inelastic energy loss during XPS measurement can be used to quantify the bandgap characters for TiO\({}_{2}\) and Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\). As mentioned in the previous literature [22, 23, 24], the bandgap values can be identified by analyzing the energy loss peak of the \(O\) 1-s spectrum obtained from XPS survey spectra. The \(O\) 1-s core levels and energy loss peaks of TiO\({}_{2}\) and Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) are shown in Fig. 3. The separation between the core-level peak energy and the onset of inelastic loss (obtained by the intersection of the sharply decreasing region of the spectrum with the baseline) is equal to the bandgap of the material. The bandgap values of Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\)(Sample A), TiO\({}_{2}\)(Sample B) are determined to be 4.9 and 3.2 eV, respectively.

According to the method provided by Kraut _et al._[25], the valence band offset \(\Delta E_{V}\) can be expressed as

\[\Delta E_{V}=\left(E_{\rm CL}^{\rm Ga_{2}O_{3}}-E_{\rm VBM}^{\rm Ga _{2}O_{3}}\right)-\left(E_{\rm CL}^{\rm TiO_{2}}-E_{\rm VBM}^{\rm TiO_{2}}\right)\] \[-\left(E_{\rm CL(Ga_{2}O_{3})}^{\rm Ga_{2}O_{3}/TiO_{2}}-E_{\rm CL (TiO_{2})}^{\rm Ga_{2}O_{3}/TiO_{2}}\right)\]

where \(E_{\rm CL}^{\rm Ga_{2}O_{3}}\) and \(E_{\rm VBM}^{\rm Ga_{2}O_{3}}\) are the core levels and valence band maximum (VBM) binding energies of Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) (Sample A), \(E_{\rm CL}^{\rm TiO_{2}}\) and \(E_{\rm VBM}^{\rm TiO_{2}}\) are the core level and VBM binding energy of TiO\({}_{2}\)(Sample B), respectively. \(E_{\rm CL(Ga_{2}O_{3})}^{\rm Ga_{2}O_{3}/TiO_{2}}\) and \(E_{\rm CL(TiO_{2})}^{\rm Ga_{2}O_{3}/TiO_{2}}\) correspond to the energy differences between Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) core level and TiO\({}_{2}\) core level of the TiO\({}_{2}\)/Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) interface (Sample C).

