As shown in Fig. 4(a)-(c), the numerical calculation results of \(\Delta\,E_{V}\) is \(-1.4\) eV. Based on the calculated bandgaps, the energy band diagrams for the TiO\({}_{2}\)/Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) interfaces are demonstrated in Fig. 4(d), which indicates that the investigated TiO\({}_{2}\)/Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) interfaces are the type I band alignment with the \(\Delta\,E_{C}\) of \(-0.3\) eV.

In addition to \(\Delta\,E_{C}\), the dielectric constant of the material is another important parameter [19]. Under a large reverse bias, the material with large dielectric constant \(\varepsilon\) has a relatively flat conduction band profile, which can effectively prevent the electron tunneling and reduce the reverse leakage current. While under forward bias, the current injected through the insulating layer can be expressed as

\[J\sim\mu\varepsilon V^{2}/L^{3} \tag{1}\]

where \(\mu\) is the electron mobility, \(\varepsilon\) is the dielectric constant, and \(L\) is the thickness of the dielectric. According to (1), at a given bias voltage, the higher the dielectric constant, the lower the voltage drop across the dielectric, thus increasing the forward current. Due to the \(\Delta\,E_{C}\) of \(-0.05\) eV and dielectric constant of 40, TiO\({}_{2}\) may be a preferable choice used in MDS diodes [20, 21].

In the following, the fabrication of \(\beta\)-Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) MDS diode is presented. As shown in Fig. 5(a), the 650 \(\mu\)m bulk \(n^{+}\) substrates with Sn doping concentration of 1.6 \(\times\) 10\({}^{19}\) cm\({}^{-3}\) (5.0 \(\times\) 5.0 \(\times\) 0.65 mm\({}^{3}\)) were grown by edge-defined film-fed growth (EFG) and the lightly doped 8-\(\mu\)m-thick \(n^{-}\beta\)-Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) (001) layers with the electron concentration of 2.5 \(\times\) 10\({}^{16}\) cm\({}^{-3}\) were deposited by halide vapor phase epitaxy (HVPE). Ohmic contact on the backside of the \(n^{+}\beta\)-Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) bulk was formed with the metal stack of Ti/Au (20 nm/100 nm) deposited by E-beam evaporation and rapid thermal annealed at 550 \({}^{\circ}\)C for 1 min under nitrogen atmosphere. After ultrasonic cleaning in acetone, ethanol, and deionized (DI) water for 10 min in each solvent, the TiO\({}_{2}\) layer with a thickness of 20 nm was grown directly on the \(\beta\)-Ga\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) substrates. Finally, the circular Schottky anode electrodes were formed by evaporation of Ni/Au (40 nm/100 nm) metal stack with diameters of 100 \(\mu\)m patterned by ultraviolet (UV) photolithography and lift-off process.

